<h2 id="video-footage-and-motion-capture-evidence">Video Footage and Motion Capture Evidence</h2>
<p>When you review video evidence, start by cataloging visible <strong>camera artifacts</strong> and glitches—lens flares, compression blocks, and rolling shutter distortions can all masquerade as anomalies. Compare <strong>motion-capture data</strong> and frame-by-frame tracking to rule out algorithmic misinterpretations or interpolation errors. Finally, demand <strong>contextual corroboration</strong>—timestamps, multiple angles, and witness reports—to separate true unexplained motion from technical or environmental causes.</p>
<h3 id="camera-artifacts-and-glitches">Camera Artifacts and Glitches</h3>
<p>Although <strong>video and motion-capture artifacts</strong> can look convincing at first glance, you should treat them as <strong>technical events</strong> subject to sensor limits, compression, and processing errors rather than as prima facie paranormal phenomena. You’ll check for <strong>camera malfunctions</strong> first: stuck pixels, rolling shutter skew, frame drops, and IR bleed can create shapes or motion that mimic agency. Then you’ll examine <strong>metadata</strong>, codec behavior, and evidence of post-processing that cause <strong>digital distortion</strong>—blockiness, chromatic aberration, or temporal interpolation artifacts. Reproduce the setup when possible, vary lighting and frame rates, and test alternative devices to isolate repeatable errors. Keep meticulous notes and timestamps so you can distinguish instrument effects from <strong>unexplained occurrences</strong>, preserving both skepticism and investigative freedom.</p>
<h3 id="motion-capture-misinterpretations">Motion Capture Misinterpretations</h3>
<p>If you’re reviewing motion-capture or video footage as evidence, don’t assume tracked points or skeletal overlays represent real intent or independent agency; they’re algorithmic constructs that can be fooled by occlusion, reflective surfaces, unusual clothing, and calibration drift. You’ll want to inspect raw frames, log files, and timestamps for motion tracking errors and shadow misinterpretations. Check for sudden pose jumps, improbable limb lengths, or anchors snapping to background features.</p>
